<h5>Final Note on Writing Titles:</h5>
<p>You'll likely have to change around your title 5-10 times before you have one that is clear and concise, evokes curiosity, and is on a topic teens are searching. Of course, there are always exceptions to the rules but the majority of your pitched article titles should meet these criteria.</p>

<h5>Choosing a thumbnail</h5>
<p>IMPORTANT: Read <a target="_blank" href="/finding-images">Finding Images</a> first to make sure you are finding images safely!</p>
<p>Once you've found some images that are royalty free, there are a few tricks to know for choosing a catchy thumbnail image. These are suggestions to keep in mind, not the rule. There are plenty of great thumbnail images that do not adhere to these observations.</p>
<ul>
  <li>BuzzFeed found that color images relay information faster than black and white ones and so they also perform better.</li>
  <li>Images in which you can see the entire body perform worse than the ones where you can just see the upper body.</li>
  <li>Images with a face are more likely to be paid attention to.</li>
  <li>Light colors almost always do better than dark ones.</li>
  <li>Pictures that look authentic and not staged almost always do better.</li>
</ul>

